summary:
I am passionate about 'making cities for people' by placing human needs at the center of planning, design and the building of healthy, resilient, and inclusive places. I place great importance and have a good eye for the small everyday places and urban interventions and their role in making life easier and more enjoyable in the city. 

My career spans the field of education and professional practice. I have twenty years of  experience in urban design teams, working on the urban regeneration of inner city areas with special attention to housing design, transport and public space improvements as well as social, cultural and sustainability issues.
 
I worked in a variety of positions and cultural contexts; as an urban designer in the private and public sector, a freelance consultant and as a lecturer in England, Bolivia and The Netherlands.

In the last few decades Coroico and the surrounding countryside have seen a large population increase which placed a heavy burden on the town’s public space, transport facilities and infrastructure. Coroico has not been able to keep up with increased construction, the many vehicles on its streets, and intensified and conflicting demands on public space. The strategy analyses the different needs and opinions on transport and public space in Coroico, and offers both short-term and long-term solutions to improve the use of public space and transport operations for the benefit of residents and those visiting Coroico. One of the tools used to bring attention to the strategy and to further the discussion on public space and transport is a time-lapse film of the street scene in town. The strategy and film were presented to the Mayor and the people of Coroico, in the presence of the German Ambassador to Bolivia, in February 2014.
